P0 [CRITICAL-JS-VIOLATION] Compilation failure: reverted structs violate where T : EventArgs constraint

SafeInvoke<T> carries the constraint where T : EventArgs, which requires T to be a reference type that inherits from EventArgs. In C#, a struct cannot inherit from any class (it implicitly inherits only from System.ValueType), so none of the 9 reverted signal types (TradeSignal, TrailUpdateSignal, StopUpdateSignal, etc.) satisfy this constraint. Every call-site such as SafeInvoke(OnTradeSignal, signal) will produce CS0315 at compile time. The where T : EventArgs constraint added in PR fix(codacy): Phase 2 - Resolve 86 ErrorProne issues #17 must be removed from SafeInvoke before the struct reversion is valid. This PR CANNOT be merged until the constraint is resolved.

src/SignalBroadcaster.cs, line 18-46 (link)

P2 Mutable struct design risk (defensive copy hazard)

All 9 signal structs expose { get; set; } auto-properties. Mutable structs in C# invite defensive-copy bugs: any time a mutable struct is read through a readonly variable, interface reference, or readonly field, mutations silently operate on a hidden copy. Changing all setters to init; (C# 9+) or marking the struct readonly would enforce immutability while preserving the zero-allocation goal.

